Display Description¶

In [4]:
print(california.DESCR)

.. _california_housing_dataset:

California Housing dataset
--------------------------

**Data Set Characteristics:**

    :Number of Instances: 20640

    :Number of Attributes: 8 numeric, predictive attributes and the target

    :Attribute Information:
        - MedInc        median income in block group
        - HouseAge      median house age in block group
        - AveRooms      average number of rooms per household
        - AveBedrms     average number of bedrooms per household
        - Population    block group population
        - AveOccup      average number of household members
        - Latitude      block group latitude
        - Longitude     block group longitude

    :Missing Attribute Values: None

This dataset was obtained from the StatLib repository.
https://www.dcc.fc.up.pt/~ltorgo/Regression/cal_housing.html

The target variable is the median house value for California districts,
expressed in hundreds of thousands of dollars ($100,000).

This dataset was derived from the 1990 U.S. census, using one row per census
block group. A block group is the smallest geographical unit for which the U.S.
Census Bureau publishes sample data (a block group typically has a population
of 600 to 3,000 people).

An household is a group of people residing within a home. Since the average
number of rooms and bedrooms in this dataset are provided per household, these
columns may take surpinsingly large values for block groups with few households
and many empty houses, such as vacation resorts.

It can be downloaded/loaded using the
:func:`sklearn.datasets.fetch_california_housing` function.

.. topic:: References

    - Pace, R. Kelley and Ronald Barry, Sparse Spatial Autoregressions,
      Statistics and Probability Letters, 33 (1997) 291-297

The charts show us some different visualizations. Most charts have a pool of dots around the top because $500,000 was the max input range. Therefore anything over that would have the same numbers. Similar there is a line of dots at 52 for the home age because that was the highest number that could be chosen. The real interesting part was that the longitiude and lattitude charts have two distinct groupings. When looking at this we must assume that there are major cities in this area. This chart helps show the disbursement of California. Our charts do not really give us a good estimate on the linear relationships between house value and the other factors.

figure = plt.figure(figsize=(9,9))

# Setting X and Y Limits

start = min(expected.min(), predicted.min())

end = max(expected.max(), predicted.max())

axes.set_xlim(start, end)

axes.set_ylim(start, end)

# Plot Line

line = plt.plot([start, end], [start, end], 'k--')

The model acutall gave a decent line here. The data seems to be somewhat evenely distributed. The Model may shy on the under side as we get higher in values but that could be from the data range limits.

Regression Model Metrics¶

Import metrics¶

from sklearn import metrics

In [42]:
# R Score

metrics.r2_score(expected, predicted)
Out[42]:
0.6008983115964333

The r2 tells us that the prediction is going to be correct roughly 60% of the time based on the independent variables.

In [43]:
# Mean Squared Error

metrics.mean_squared_error(expected, predicted)
Out[43]:
0.5350149774449119

When using this, the closer to zero, the better the area fits our data.

Choosing the Best Model¶

In [45]:
# Import Models

from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet, Lasso, Ridge

Estimators¶

estimators={ 'LinearRegression': linear_regression, 'EleasticNet': ElasticNet(), 'Lasso': Lasso(), 'Ridge': Ridge() }

In [47]:
# Import KFold

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, cross_val_score
In [50]:
# Find the best method

for estimator_name, estimator_object in estimators.items():
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=11, shuffle=True)
    scores = cross_val_score(estimator=estimator_object, 
                             X=california.data, y=california.target, cv=kfold,
                             scoring='r2')
    print(f'{estimator_name:>16}: ' + f'mean of r2 scores={scores.mean():.3f}')

LinearRegression: mean of r2 scores=0.599
     EleasticNet: mean of r2 scores=0.423
           Lasso: mean of r2 scores=0.285
           Ridge: mean of r2 scores=0.599

LinearRegression and Ridge have the same r2 score. Because they have the same score, either model would be best to use for predicting the outcome.
